Since we have already determined Stock A's portfolio weight, we can now compute for the risk-free asset's portfolio weight by subtracting 100\% by Stock A's portfolio weight. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}

\text{Portfolio weight, Risk-free asset}&={\text{ 100\% - 82.14\%}}\\

&={\textbf{17.86\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The portfolio weight of the risk-free asset is 17.86%.**

Since we have already determined Stock A's portfolio weight, we can now compute for the risk-free asset's portfolio weight by subtracting 100\% by Stock A's portfolio weight. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}

\text{Portfolio weight, Risk-free asset}&={\text{ 100\% - 200\%}}\\

&={\textbf{-100\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The risk-free asset has a portfolio weight of -100%, which means the profitability of the investment is negatively correlated with the profitability of the inadequate stock is proportional to its weight.**
